"Tips are dead-end paths in de Bruijn graphs that arise from sequencing errors. Short tips (under 2k length) are removed because they are characteristic of errors."
Velvet defines tip removal criteria of length and minority count: a tip is only removed if it is shorter than 2k, since this length exceeds the k-mer length of an individual short read, making erroneous constructs involving entire reads extremely rare. Amazon Web Services
Citation: Zerbino DR, Birney E. Velvet: algorithms for de novo short read assembly using de Bruijn graphs. Genome Research. 2008;18(5):821-829. https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2336801/
"Three main categories of graph errors require cleaning: tips, bubbles, and bulges."
Rizzi et al. describe three main categories of graph errors that require cleaning: tips (short dead-end paths diverging from the main path), bubbles (parallel short paths that start and end in the same two nodes), and bulges (short low-coverage paths that create alternate paths between two nodes), and note that residual bubbles in the graph are usually considered heterozygous loci. Valebyte
Citation: Rizzi R, Beretta S, Patterson M, et al. Overlap graphs and de Bruijn graphs: data structures for de novo genome assembly in the big data era. Quantitative Biology. 2019;7(4):278-292. https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1007/s40484-019-0181-x
"Bubbles in de Bruijn graphs come from either errors or biological variants like SNPs."
Velvet states that bubbles can be created by errors or biological variants such as SNPs or cloning artifacts prior to sequencing, and erroneous bubbles are removed by an algorithm called "Tour Bus" while criteria for deciding whether to simplify two paths can take into account error models or other features such as coverage. Hlrs
Citation: Same Velvet paper (Zerbino & Birney 2008) above.
"SNPs and biological variants appear as bubbles in de Bruijn graphs."
SNPs appear as "bubbles" in de Bruijn graphs and calling SNPs amounts to searching for these bubbles, with multiple tools designed for this purpose including those by Iqbal et al. 2012, Leggett et al. 2013, and Uricaru et al. 2015. San José State University Library
Primary citation: Iqbal Z, Caccamo M, Turner I, Flicek P, McVean G. De novo assembly and genotyping of variants using colored de Bruijn graphs. Nature Genetics. 2012;44(2):226-232. https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3272472/
"The k-mer multiplicity histogram has an error peak on the left from sequencing errors and a signal peak on the right from real genomic content; the valley between them is the threshold."
The left peak of the k-mer histogram primarily comprises k-mers that are a result of sequencing errors and biases, occurring at low frequency. The right tail comprises repetitive fragments from the genome occurring at higher frequency. GWDG
The lowest point of the first valley is the point of overlap between the error peak and the first visible biological peak. At high sequencing depth, nearly all k-mers from k-mer coverage groups at or below that point are likely error k-mers. GWDG
