"k-mer size affects the trade-off between bubble detection sensitivity and gap probability."
As k-mer size increases, the fraction of SNP sites with unconfounded bubbles ranges from 51% with k=21 to 85% with k=75 in humans. Increasing k-mer size reduces the risk of error-induced contigs confounding the graph, but also increases the probability of a k-mer containing an error. For a fixed per-base depth and read-length, as k-mer size increases, the effective depth of each k-mer decreases leading to an increased probability of gaps in the assembly. Princeton Research Computing
